07983nam a22008295i 9781554588626DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545886267 a10.51644/97815545886262doi  a(DE-B1597)667451  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLIT0040802bisacsh00aTrans/acting Culture, Writing, and Memory :bEssays in Honour of Barbara Godard /ced. by Ray Ellenwood, Jennifer Henderson, Eva C. Karpinski, Ian Sowton. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (396 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransCanada00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tEditors’ Introduction -- tReader at Work: An Appreciation of Barbara Godard -- tTextual/Visual Production: Critical Interventions -- tIncisive Literary Critic, Brilliant Theorist, Engaged Teacher, Inspired Translator, Public Intellectual, and Committed Activist—All in the Feminine: The Early Barbara Godard -- tCultural Memory and Tragic Affect in Nancy Huston’s The Mark of the Angel -- tLanguage and Interdisciplinarity: (Re-)contextualizing Nicole Brossard’s Picture Theory -- tWriting the Museum: Visual Art and Literature: Denise Desautels and Louise Warren -- tCulture/Policy/Institutions -- tNegotiating Literatures in Contiguity: France Daigle in/and Québec -- tA Lack of Public Memory: A Public Memory of Lack -- t“The Toil and Spoil of Translation”: A Godardian Reading of the Study-Guide: Discover Canada/Guide d’étude: Découvrir le Canada (2010) -- tNotes Toward Thinking Transsexual Institutional Poetics -- tTranslation/Transculturation -- tVoyage autour de la traduction: The Translator as Writer and Theorist -- tTaking Deleuze in the Middle, or Doing Intellectual History by the Letter -- tGail Scott and Barbara Godard on “The Main”: Borders, Sutures, Micro-cosmopolitan Interconnectivity, and Translation Studies -- tPublic Memory and the Archive -- tLinked Histories and Radio-Activity in Marie Clements’s Burning Vision -- tMemory as Fracture: French Mnemotechniques in the Erasure of the Holocaust -- tGender in the Shaping of Public Memory: Arms (Monumental) for Montreal -- tContested Memories: Canadian Women Writers in and out of the Archive -- tIn the Stacks of Barbara Godard, or Do Not Confuse the Complexity of This Moment with Chaos -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tBooks in the TransCanada Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTrans/acting Culture, Writing, and Memory is a collection of essays written in honour of Barbara Godard, one of the most original and wide-ranging literary critics, theorists, teachers, translators, and public intellectuals Canada has ever produced. The contributors, both established and emerging scholars, extend Godard’s work through engagements with her published texts in the spirit of creative interchange and intergenerational relay of ideas. Their essays resonate with Godard’s innovative scholarship, situated at the intersection of such fields as literary studies, cultural studies, translation studies, feminist theory, arts criticism, social activism, institutional analysis, and public memory. In pursuit of unexpected linkages and connections, the essays venture beyond generic and disciplinary borders, zeroing in on Godard’s transdisciplinary practice which has been extremely influential in the way it framed questions and modelled interventions for the study of Canadian, Québécois, and Acadian literatures and cultures. The authors work with the materials ranging from Canadian government policies and documents to publications concerning white-supremacist organizations in Southern Ontario, online materials from a Toronto-based transgender arts festival, a photographic mural installation commemorating the Montreal Massacre, and the works of such writers and artists as Marie Clements, Nicole Brossard, France Daigle, Nancy Huston, Yvette Nolan, Gail Scott, Denise Desautels, Louise Warren, Rebecca Belmore, Vera Frenkel, Robert Lepage, and Janet Cardiff.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aCollective memory and literature. 0aFeminism and literature. 0aLiterature and transnationalism. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAntwi, Phanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapperdoni, Alessandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemers, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorland, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllenwood, Ray, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFindlay, Len M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForsyth, Louise H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodard, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJirgens, Karl E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarpinski, Eva C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarpinski, Eva C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLane-Mercier, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeclerc, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Sue, econtributor.4